14 (D) THE FOLLOWING INFORMATIONAL SHEET MAY BE USED TO EXPLAIN
15 THE FORM FOR TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED:
16 COMMON QUESTIONS ABOUT THE USE OF THIS FORM
17 THIS INFORMATIONAL SHEET SHOULD NOT BE RECORDED WITH
18 A TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED AT THE DEPARTMENT OF LAND
19 RECORDS IN THE OFFICE OF THE CLERK OF THE CIRCUIT COURT.
20 SHOULD I CONSULT AN ATTORNEY PRIOR TO COMPLETING THIS FORM? IT IS
21 ALWAYS RECOMMENDED THAT YOU SPEAK WITH AN ATTORNEY BEFORE SIGNING A
22 DEED, AND THIS FORM MAY NOT BE APPROPRIATE FOR ALL CIRCUMSTANCES. THIS
23 FORM MAY NOT BE APPROPRIATE IF YOUR NAME IS NOT ON THE CURRENT DEED TO
24 THE PROPERTY, YOUR CURRENT LEGAL NAME IS DIFFERENT THAN YOUR NAME ON
25 THE CURRENT DEED, YOU OWN THE PROPERTY WITH OTHER INDIVIDUALS, OR YOU
26 WANT TO NAME MULTIPLE PEOPLE TO INHERIT YOUR PROPERTY TOGETHER.
27 WHAT DOES THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED DO? WHEN YOU DIE, THIS DEED
28 TRANSFERS THE DESCRIBED PROPERTY, SUBJECT TO CERTAIN SECURITY

24 HOUSE BILL 738
1 AGREEMENTS ON THE PROPERTY, SUBJECT TO ANY LIENS, MORTGAGES, OR OTHER
2 ENCUMBRANCES ON THE PROPERTY AT YOUR DEATH. PROBATE IS NOT REQUIRED.
3 THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED HAS NO EFFECT UNTIL YOU DIE. YOU CAN REVOKE
4 IT AT ANY TIME. YOU ARE ALSO FREE TO TRANSFER THE PROPERTY TO SOMEONE
5 ELSE DURING YOUR LIFETIME. IF YOU DO NOT OWN ANY INTEREST IN THE PROPERTY
6 WHEN YOU DIE, THIS DEED WILL HAVE NO EFFECT.
7 HOW DO I MAKE A TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED? COMPLETE THIS FORM.
8 HAVE IT ACKNOWLEDGED BEFORE A NOTARY PUBLIC OR OTHER INDIVIDUAL
9 AUTHORIZED UNDER LAW TO TAKE ACKNOWLEDGMENTS. RECORD THE FORM IN
10 EACH COUNTY WHERE ANY PART OF THE PROPERTY IS LOCATED. THE FORM HAS NO
11 EFFECT UNLESS IT IS ACKNOWLEDGED AND RECORDED BEFORE YOUR DEATH.
12 IS THE “LEGAL DESCRIPTION” OF THE PROPERTY NECESSARY? YES.
13 HOW DO I FIND THE “LEGAL DESCRIPTION” OF THE PROPERTY? THIS
14 INFORMATION MAY BE ON THE DEED YOU RECEIVED WHEN YOU BECAME AN OWNER
15 OF THE PROPERTY AND MAY BE FOUND IN A PARAGRAPH THAT STARTS WITH THE
16 WORDS “BEGINNING” OR “BEING”. THIS INFORMATION MAY ALSO BE AVAILABLE IN
17 THE OFFICE OF THE CLERK OF THE CIRCUIT COURT FOR THE COUNTY WHERE THE
18 PROPERTY IS LOCATED. IF YOU ARE NOT ABSOLUTELY SURE, CONSULT A LAWYER.
19 WHAT HAPPENS IF I SELECT MULTIPLE BENEFICIARIES? IF THIS FORM NAMES
20 MULTIPLE PRIMARY AND/OR ALTERNATE BENEFICIARIES AND YOU DO NOT
21 INDICATE A DIFFERENT FORM OF OWNERSHIP, THE PROPERTY WILL BE
22 TRANSFERRED TO THEM AS JOINT TENANTS WITH RIGHT OF SURVIVORSHIP. IF YOU
23 ARE NOT SURE WHETHER THIS IS THE APPROPRIATE OWNERSHIP STRUCTURE FOR
24 YOUR BENEFICIARIES, CONSULT WITH AN ATTORNEY.
25 CAN I CHANGE MY MIND BEFORE I RECORD THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED?
26 YES. IF YOU HAVE NOT YET RECORDED THE DEED AND WANT TO CHANGE YOUR
27 MIND, SIMPLY TEAR UP OR OTHERWISE DESTROY THE DEED.
28 WHICH CONTROLS AT MY DEATH, MY WILL OR THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH
29 DEED? THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED CONTROLS OVER A CONTRARY
30 INSTRUCTION IN A WILL.
31 HOW DO I “RECORD” THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED? TAKE THE
32 COMPLETED AND ACKNOWLEDGED FORM TO THE CLERK OF THE CIRCUIT COURT
33 FOR THE COUNTY WHERE THE PROPERTY IS LOCATED. FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS
34 GIVEN BY THE CLERK’S OFFICE TO MAKE THE FORM PART OF THE OFFICIAL
35 PROPERTY RECORDS. IF THE PROPERTY IS IN MORE THAN ONE COUNTY, YOU
36 SHOULD RECORD THE DEED IN EACH COUNTY.

HOUSE BILL 738 25
1 DOES A TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED HELP AVOID INHERITANCE TAXES? NO.
2 YOUR BENEFICIARY MAY NEED TO PAY INHERITANCE TAXES AS A RESULT OF THE
3 TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED. IF YOU HAVE QUESTIONS RELATED TO INHERITANCE
4 TAXES, CONSULT A LAWYER.
5 CAN I LATER REVOKE THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED IF I CHANGE MY
6 MIND? YES. YOU CAN REVOKE THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED. NO ONE,
7 INCLUDING THE BENEFICIARIES, CAN PREVENT YOU FROM REVOKING THE DEED.
8 HOW DO I REVOKE THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED AFTER IT IS RECORDED?
9 THERE ARE THREE WAYS TO REVOKE A RECORDED TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED: (1)
10 COMPLETE AND ACKNOWLEDGE A REVOCATION FORM, AND RECORD IT IN EACH
11 COUNTY WHERE THE PROPERTY IS LOCATED. (2) COMPLETE AND ACKNOWLEDGE A
12 NEW TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED THAT DISPOSES OF THE SAME PROPERTY, AND
13 RECORD IT IN EACH COUNTY WHERE THE PROPERTY IS LOCATED. (3) TRANSFER THE
14 PROPERTY TO SOMEONE ELSE DURING YOUR LIFETIME BY A RECORDED DEED THAT
15 EXPRESSLY REVOKES THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED. YOU MAY NOT REVOKE THE
16 TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED BY WILL.
17 I AM BEING PRESSURED TO COMPLETE THIS FORM. WHAT SHOULD I DO? DO
18 NOT COMPLETE THIS FORM UNDER PRESSURE. SEEK HELP FROM A TRUSTED
19 FAMILY MEMBER, FRIEND, OR LAWYER.
20 DO I NEED TO TELL THE BENEFICIARIES ABOUT THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH
21 DEED? NO, BUT IT IS STRONGLY RECOMMENDED. SECRECY NON–DISCLOSURE CAN
22 CAUSE LATER COMPLICATIONS AND MIGHT MAKE IT EASIER FOR OTHERS TO
23 COMMIT FRAUD.
24 COULD A TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED I RECORD TODAY BE AFFECTED IF I
25 DIVORCE LATER OR GET MARRIED AND HAVE CHILDREN? YES. IF YOU CREATE A
26 TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED THAT NAMES YOUR SPOUSE AS THE BENEFICIARY
27 WHILE YOU ARE MARRIED AND YOU LATER DIVORCE OR YOUR MARRIAGE IS
28 ANNULLED, THE TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED WILL BE CONSIDERED TO BE
29 AUTOMATICALLY REVOKED. ADDITIONALLY, IF YOU RECORD A
30 TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED NAMING ANY BENEFICIARY AND LATER MARRY AND
31 HAVE CHILDREN WITH YOUR FUTURE SPOUSE BY BIRTH, ADOPTION, OR
32 LEGITIMATION, YOUR TRANSFER–ON–DEATH DEED WILL BE CONSIDERED TO BE
33 AUTOMATICALLY REVOKED.
34 AS A BENEFICIARY, WHAT DO I DO ONCE THE OWNER HAS DIED? YOU WILL
35 AUTOMATICALLY RECEIVE THE PROPERTY WHEN THE OWNER DIES, UNLESS YOU
36 FOLLOW MARYLAND’S PROCEDURE TO DISCLAIM YOUR INTEREST. YOU MAY WISH

